Whole Game: Analyzing deforestation

0.1 Introduction

For this module, we’ll focus on generating a report using targets. We’ll create each result as a series of targets, including them in _targets.R. We’ll iterate through, one or two targets at a time, running tar_make() and tar_visnetwork() to check our work. Check exercises.Rmd for guidance on creating this report! This will be an intentionally simplified report: we’ll focus on the basics of creating output as targets and including them here as rendered material.

0.2 Methods

In this analysis, we look at the net change in forestation in 2010 as well as the causes of deforestation in Brazil. These data come from Our World in Data.

0.3 Results

Figure 1: Net Forest Conversion in 2010

Figure 1 presents a map of net forest conversion in 2010, as well as the 10 countries with the highest absolute change in forest. In 2010, the China gained more forest than any other country, a net growth of 1,936,770 hectacres; Brazil lost more forest than any other country, a net loss of -1,539,180 hectacres.

Table 1: Causes of Brazilian forest loss in 2010
Cause Hectacres
Pasture 616,000
Fire 537,000
Small scale clearing 271,000
Selective logging 114,000
Commercial crops 100,000
Natural disturbances 44,000
Roads 22,000
Other infrastructure 9,000
Tree plantations including palm 9,000
Mining 4,000
Flooding due to dams 0
Total 1,726,000

Table 1 shows the causes of deforestation in Brazil in 2010. The top cause was clearing for pasture (616,000 hectacres), followed by fire (537,000 hectacres), then small scale clearing (271,000 hectacres).

Figure 2: Causes of deforestation in Brazil over time, sorted by maximum loss

Figure 2 shows that, while deforestation has decreased in Brazil since the early 2000s, it remains steady at over 1 million hectacres lost per year. Pasture clearing is consistently the top cause, while fire—generally being accidental—varies from year to year.

0.4 Discussion

We’ve combined the magic of R Markdown for generating reports with the reliability of targets for managing our code, when we render the report, and understanding what targets the report depends on. targets also let’s us focus more on communicating and less on including lots of code in our report; it’s all handled by our pipeline. Using tar_load() and tar_read() allows us to grab targets and associated them with this report!
